    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, let's dive deeper into the scientific details of Anaphase and complete the explanation with Cytokinesis.\n\nDuring Anaphase, the sister chromatids, which were previously joined together, are pulled apart by the spindle fibers. These fibers are made of a protein called tubulin, and they emanate from the centrosomes, which are the microtubule organizing centers of the cell. As the cell progresses through Anaphase, the spindle fibers shorten, pulling the sister chromatids towards opposite poles of the cell. This movement is facilitated by motor proteins called dyneins and kinesins, which \"walk\" along the microtubules, carrying the chromatids with them. The separation of the sister chromatids ensures that each new daughter cell will receive an identical set of chromosomes.\n\nFollowing Anaphase, the cell enters Telophase, where the chromosomes arrive at the poles and begin to decondense, returning to their less compact form. The nuclear envelope re-forms around each set of chromosomes, creating two separate nuclei within the cell. This marks the near completion of mitosis.\n\nHowever, the cell division process is not yet complete. This is where Cytokinesis comes in. Cytokinesis is the physical process of dividing",
      "source": "target",
